[4] Attacks
- Mon 16 Dec 2019
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease research and Policy), abridged, edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/12/more-violence-beni-drc-tracks-new-ebola-cases
[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

Over the weekend at least 43 people, including a pregnant woman, were killed in Beni, one of the epicenters of the DRC's current Ebola outbreak, as officials tallied 8 new cases of the deadly disease.

The rebel terrorist organization Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) likely conducted the attacks, according to the Associated Press (AP) and Al Jazeera.

Last month [November 2019], clashes between the DRC's military and the ADF led the World Health Organization (WHO) to temporarily pull its Ebola response teams out of the area, after health workers were killed during the skirmishes.

The violence has made contact tracing and vaccination difficult, and has since led to an uptick of cases just weeks after WHO officials said the outbreak was almost contained.

Rebels pit civilians against military
-------------------------------------
The AP said the 1st attack began the night of [13 Dec 2019], when at least 6 people were killed in Beni, including a pregnant woman. Al Jazeera said 22 more people were killed in an attack on [14 Dec 2019], also in the same city.

All told, the AP said today [Mon 16 Dec 2019] that 43 people died over the weekend in Beni, including several who were shot as ADF militants went door to door in communities surrounding Beni yesterday [Sun 15 Dec 2019].

According to human rights organizations interviewed by the AP, ADF's goal is to pit civilians against the DRC military. The ADF, which has been associated with the Islamic State, is active in eastern DRC.

As of today [Mon 16 Dec 2019], the WHO's Ebola dashboard shows 8 new cases recorded over the weekend, including 2 cases today. The outbreak total now stands at 3348, including 2210 fatalities. Officials are still investigation 437 suspected cases.

Violent attacks have almost always spurred on new Ebola cases in their wake during the 17-month-long outbreak in the eastern part of the DRC.

The DRC's Ebola technical committee (CMRE) said cases over the weekend were in Mabalako.

